There is currently one nest box that is connected to our home Wi-Fi.
The other nest box will need some work before it can go online.
Alright, I hung the new nest box up during the day. This is how it looks in the garden.
But let's take a moment to go back. It seems no one asked, "What's inside?"
At the top is an ESP32 camera board with a fisheye lens camera and an infrared LED light that I took from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The plastic box has an unusual shape because the side panels of the nest box can rotate. When I bought it, it was like this and couldn't be modified, so I had to design according to this situation.
Since there's no power supply in the garden, the entire device is powered by a solar panel and a 2600mAh 18650 lithium-ion battery.
I didn't take photos of the battery or charger, but here is the photo of the solar panel.
The gray box hanging on the side of the nest box contains the battery.
Once fully charged, it can run for approximately 4 hours.
I call this the "special feature." This way, the birds do get some private space.
Initially, I wasn't sure if the network in the garden was strong enough to support this setup. The old access points I replaced last autumn certainly wouldn't cut it.
But the new access point has a fine coverage range.
Now, I don't even need to install a TP-Link CPE210 on the roof pointing down at the garden.
If I were to set up more nesting boxes with cameras in the future, I might still do this. Especially in places farther away from the house, where I might need it.
Now, the camera went offline for reasons I'm not quite sure about. It stops working just an hour after sunset.
Maybe it's because it stops charging three hours before sunset due to insufficient light.
Maybe half a day isn't enough to fully charge it.
Let's see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have telemetry data for the battery. I might add this feature in future versions.
