Sigh, nothing worthwhile is ever easy.
Turns out, the 5V line and GND line on the USB-C splitter board used to connect the battery charger were printed in reverse.
After swapping the wires, the charging indicator light came on.
ESP is not online yet. Let's wait a few more minutes.
An hour has passed, and it is still offline.
It seems it is stuck in a reboot loop, triggering the reset function of Tasmota.
This board is really garbage. I have ordered a larger one and hope it will solve the problem.
See what I found in the workshop.
This is a 24V solar panel. Unfortunately, the sun is too low (and there is a tree obstructing it), and the voltage dropped significantly as soon as I added a load.
It seems I won't know if this solar panel is sufficient or if I need the better-performing one I ordered until tomorrow.
The information on Amazon shows that this solar panel was purchased in 2021 with a maximum output of 12V 1.2A.
So either this solar panel is faulty, my multimeter is, or they changed the product page.
Hello everyone, good news!
They changed the product page, and this one I have is faulty.
The title on both the old and new product pages calls it a 12V 10W solar panel.
This is why I didn't delete the old emails.
Hey, look: It reconnected about an hour ago, but only for less than a minute.
Maybe the solar panel gave the battery just enough charge to run for 38 seconds. That’s about two hours' worth of time.
Guess what: it's cloudy today! So I'm not sure if that (possibly broken) solar panel can generate enough power to work.
Let's wait and see.
Latest update: the new solar panel is installed, and it now seems to be working properly.
Maybe it will shut down once the sun sets, but let's wait and see.
Interestingly, I am using Home Assistant's ping integration to monitor whether it is online.
The average round-trip time is 102 milliseconds. Not great, but not bad.
